Biochemical evidence for evolution
Different species share genetic (DNA) similarities as well as anatomical/structural ones. DNA was not around when Darwin was, so he couldn’t use this as a form of evidence in his theory of evolution.  However, in the modern theory of evolution genetics has been added as further evidence for the process.  Roundworms, for example, share 25% of their genes with humans. These genes are slightly different in each species, but their striking similarities nevertheless reveal their common ancestry. In fact, the DNA code itself is a similarity that links all life on Earth to a common ancestor. DNA and RNA possess a simple four-base code (A,T,C,G) that provides the recipe for all living things. In some cases, if we were to transfer genetic material from the cell of one living thing to the cell of another, the recipient would follow the new instructions as if they were its own.  These characteristics of life demonstrate the fundamental sameness of all living things on Earth and serve as the basis of today's efforts at genetic engineering. Other biochemical ( molecular) evidence for evolution includes, similar DNA, similar RNA, similar amino acid sequences, & similar proteins ( enzymes/hormones/antibodies/pigments).  

